/* ============================================================
   Reasoning GP — 45-second explainer: EXPANSION pack
   Adds patient-friendly model explanations covering the rest of
   the Hot Seat case bank. Appends to window.SCA_EXPLAINER.
   Load AFTER sca-explainer-data.js.
   Each: c=condition, t=topic, m=model ~45s explanation, b=must-hit beats
   ============================================================ */
window.SCA_EXPLAINER = (window.SCA_EXPLAINER || []).concat([

  /* ---------- Cardiovascular ---------- */
  { c:'Angina', t:'Cardiovascular', m:'Angina is a warning sign, not a heart attack. The arteries feeding the heart muscle have narrowed, so when you exert yourself and the heart needs more, the supply can\u2019t keep up \u2014 like a partly blocked pipe that\u2019s fine at rest but struggles under demand. That\u2019s the tight, heavy chest pain that comes on with effort and eases with rest. We treat it two ways: a spray that opens the arteries for attacks, and daily tablets that protect the heart and cut your risk long-term. The key safety point \u2014 if the pain comes on at rest, lasts more than 10\u201315 minutes, or doesn\u2019t settle with the spray, that could be a heart attack: call 999.', b:['Supply-vs-demand pipe analogy','Comes with effort, eases with rest','Spray + protective tablets','Distinguish from heart attack','999 triggers'] },
  { c:'Postural hypotension', t:'Cardiovascular', m:'When you stand up, gravity pulls blood down to your legs, and your body normally tightens the vessels instantly to keep blood going to the brain. In your case that reflex is a bit slow, so for a few seconds the brain is short-changed \u2014 that\u2019s the dizziness and light-headedness. It\u2019s common with age and some blood-pressure tablets. The fixes are mostly simple: stand up slowly in stages, keep well hydrated, and we\u2019ll review any medicines that might be over-doing it. The thing I want to prevent is a fall, so take your time getting up. Come back if you actually black out, rather than just feel woozy.', b:['Standing/gravity reflex explanation','Link to age/medication','Stand slowly + hydration','Review medicines','Falls/blackout safety-net'] },
  { c:'Palpitations (benign)', t:'Cardiovascular', m:'Palpitations just mean you\u2019ve become aware of your own heartbeat \u2014 it might race, thump or skip. Most of the time this is the heart doing something completely normal that you\u2019ve simply noticed, often triggered by caffeine, stress, tiredness or alcohol. The heart isn\u2019t damaged by it. I do want to check a tracing of your heart and your bloods to be sure there\u2019s no underlying rhythm problem or thyroid issue. If those are clear, the reassurance itself usually helps, along with easing back on caffeine. Come back urgently if the palpitations come with chest pain, breathlessness or blacking out \u2014 that combination we take seriously.', b:['Awareness-of-heartbeat explanation','Common benign triggers','ECG + bloods to be safe','Reassurance + caffeine','Red-flag combination'] },

  /* ---------- Respiratory ---------- */
  { c:'Pneumonia', t:'Respiratory', m:'Pneumonia is an infection deep in the lung tissue itself, not just the airways \u2014 a patch of lung fills with inflammation and fluid, so it can\u2019t do its job of getting oxygen in. That\u2019s the fever, the cough with phlegm, and feeling wiped out and breathless. A course of antibiotics treats the infection, and most people recover well at home with rest, fluids and regular paracetamol. It can take a few weeks to feel fully back to normal, and a tired cough can linger. Come back urgently \u2014 or 999 \u2014 if you get more breathless, confused, your lips go blue, or you\u2019re not improving after two or three days.', b:['Infection in lung tissue, not just airways','Symptoms explained','Antibiotics + supportive care','Slow recovery is normal','Deterioration safety-net'] },
  { c:'Pulmonary embolism', t:'Respiratory', m:'A pulmonary embolism is a blood clot that has travelled to the lungs and lodged in one of the blood vessels there, blocking part of the lung\u2019s blood supply \u2014 that\u2019s why it causes sudden breathlessness and a sharp pain when you breathe in. It\u2019s serious, but very treatable. The mainstay is a blood thinner, which stops the clot growing and lets your body break it down over time; you\u2019ll be on it for several months. We\u2019ll also look for why it happened. Seek emergency help straight away for sudden severe breathlessness, chest pain, coughing blood, or feeling faint \u2014 this is a condition we treat urgently.', b:['Clot blocking lung vessel','Why breathless + pleuritic pain','Blood thinner for months','Look for cause','Emergency red flags'] },
  { c:'Obstructive sleep apnoea', t:'Respiratory', m:'When you sleep, the muscles in your throat relax, and in your case the airway becomes floppy enough to collapse and block \u2014 you stop breathing for a few seconds, your brain briefly wakes to restart it, and this happens over and over without you knowing. That\u2019s why you snore, stop-start, and feel exhausted all day despite a \u201cfull\u201d night. It matters because it raises blood pressure and the daytime sleepiness affects driving. A sleep study confirms it, and a mask called CPAP, which gently splints the airway open, is hugely effective \u2014 most people feel transformed. I do need to talk to you about driving and the DVLA, because safety comes first.', b:['Airway collapse in sleep explanation','Why tired despite sleeping','Health + driving consequences','Sleep study + CPAP','DVLA/driving safety'] },
  { c:'Allergic rhinitis (hay fever)', t:'Respiratory', m:'Hay fever is your immune system over-reacting to something harmless like pollen, treating it as a threat and flooding the nose with inflammation \u2014 hence the sneezing, blocked, runny nose and itchy eyes. The single most useful treatment is a steroid nose spray used every day through the season, not just when you\u2019re bad \u2014 and used correctly, aiming away from the middle of the nose. Add a non-drowsy antihistamine and eye drops if needed. Most \u201cit doesn\u2019t work\u201d is really irregular use or poor technique. One thing to know for the future: if you ever get a one-sided blocked nose or one-sided bleeding, that\u2019s different and worth checking.', b:['Immune over-reaction explanation','Daily steroid spray is the mainstay','Correct technique','Antihistamine/eye drops add-on','Unilateral red-flag note'] },

  /* ---------- Gut ---------- */
  { c:'Anal fissure', t:'Gut', m:'A fissure is a small tear in the skin at the back passage, usually caused by passing a hard, large stool \u2014 which is why it feels like passing glass, with bright red blood on the paper and a lingering spasm afterwards. The pain makes you dread going, which causes more constipation and more tearing, so the key to healing is breaking that cycle: keep the stool soft and easy with plenty of fluids, fibre and a stool softener. A warm bath and a numbing or healing ointment help the spasm. Most heal within a few weeks. Come back if it doesn\u2019t settle, or if the bleeding changes \u2014 darker, or mixed in the stool \u2014 so I can look further.', b:['Tear from hard stool','Pain\u2013constipation\u2013spasm cycle','Soften stool is the cornerstone','Bath/ointment for spasm','Safety-net changing bleeding'] },
  { c:'Haemorrhoids', t:'Gut', m:'Haemorrhoids are swollen, cushion-like blood vessels in the back passage \u2014 we all have these cushions, but straining, constipation or pregnancy makes them enlarge and bleed. The bleeding is typically bright red, on the paper or in the bowl, and usually painless, sometimes with itch or a lump. Most settle with simple measures: softer stools through fluids and fibre, not straining or sitting too long on the toilet, and a soothing cream for a short while. If they\u2019re troublesome there are quick clinic procedures. Importantly, I won\u2019t just assume it\u2019s piles \u2014 if there\u2019s a change in your bowel habit, weight loss, or darker blood, I\u2019ll check further to rule out other causes.', b:['Swollen vessel cushions explanation','Bright red, usually painless','Soften stool + don\u2019t strain','Procedures if troublesome','Don\u2019t miss bowel cancer'] },
  { c:'Diverticular disease', t:'Gut', m:'Over the years, small pouches can form in the wall of the lower bowel \u2014 think of weak spots ballooning out, a bit like the inner tube poking through a worn tyre. Often they cause nothing, but they can give crampy left-sided pain and unpredictable bowels. We manage it with a high-fibre diet and plenty of fluids to keep things moving smoothly. Sometimes a pouch gets inflamed \u2014 that\u2019s diverticulitis \u2014 with more constant pain and a fever, which may need antibiotics. Get urgent help for severe pain with fever, or significant bleeding. And because bowel symptoms can have other causes, I\u2019ll keep an open mind and test if anything changes.', b:['Pouches/weak-spots analogy','Fibre + fluids management','Diverticulitis = inflamed pouch + fever','Urgent red flags','Keep cancer in mind'] },
  { c:'Inflammatory bowel disease', t:'Gut', m:'Crohn\u2019s and ulcerative colitis are conditions where the immune system mistakenly attacks the lining of the bowel, causing inflammation, ulcers and bleeding \u2014 which is why you get diarrhoea, sometimes with blood, cramping pain and tiredness. It\u2019s different from a simple upset because it\u2019s long-term and comes in flares. The good news is treatment has come a long way: medicines that calm the immune attack can settle flares and keep you well for long stretches, looked after by the gut specialists alongside us. We\u2019ll monitor for flares and side-effects. Seek urgent help for a severe flare \u2014 many bloody stools a day, fever, severe pain or feeling very unwell.', b:['Immune attack on bowel lining','Flaring, long-term nature','Specialist-led immune treatment','Shared monitoring','Severe flare safety-net'] },
  { c:'Chronic constipation', t:'Gut', m:'Constipation means stool is moving through the bowel too slowly, so it sits longer, water gets reabsorbed, and it becomes hard and difficult to pass. It\u2019s rarely anything sinister \u2014 usually a mix of not enough fibre or fluid, being less active, or certain medicines. The plan is to make the stool soft and the bowel active again: more fluid and fibre, regular movement, and a laxative to get you over the hump \u2014 we choose the type to suit you. Don\u2019t worry about going daily; regular and comfortable is the goal. I\u2019ll just check there are no warning signs first \u2014 weight loss, bleeding or a recent change in habit would prompt me to look further.', b:['Slow transit \u2192 hard stool explanation','Common reversible causes','Fluid/fibre/activity + laxative','Reassure on frequency','Red-flag screen'] },
  { c:'Gallstones', t:'Gut', m:'Gallstones are small stones that form in the gallbladder, the little pouch that stores bile to help digest fat. Most cause no trouble, but if a stone temporarily blocks the outflow \u2014 often after a fatty meal \u2014 you get that intense, gripping pain under the right ribs that can spread to the back, lasting up to a few hours. The definitive treatment for troublesome stones is keyhole surgery to remove the gallbladder, which you can live perfectly well without. In the meantime, lower-fat meals reduce attacks. Seek urgent help if the pain lasts many hours, you develop a fever, or you turn yellow \u2014 that means a stone is causing a blockage or infection.', b:['Stones in bile-storing gallbladder','Fatty-meal trigger, RUQ pain','Keyhole removal is definitive','Low-fat interim advice','Fever/jaundice red flags'] },
  { c:'Cannabis hyperemesis syndrome', t:'Gut', m:'This is a condition I want to be honest with you about, because the cause surprises most people. Long-term regular cannabis use can, paradoxically, cause these repeated severe vomiting attacks \u2014 and the giveaway is that hot showers or baths are the only thing that helps. That\u2019s why all the scans and tests have come back normal: it\u2019s not a problem they can see, it\u2019s the cannabis. The only thing that truly stops it is stopping cannabis \u2014 the attacks settle with abstinence and return if you use again. The usual anti-sickness tablets often don\u2019t work well. I\u2019m not here to judge; I can refer you for support to make stopping easier.', b:['Cannabis as the cause','Hot-bathing clue','Why tests are normal','Cessation is the cure','Non-judgemental support'] },
  { c:'Infantile colic', t:'Children', m:'Colic is the name we give to a healthy baby who cries inconsolably for long stretches, often in the evenings, pulling their legs up \u2014 and the reassuring news is it\u2019s extremely common and harmless. I\u2019ve examined your baby and she\u2019s thriving and well, with no signs of anything wrong. We don\u2019t fully know the cause, but it isn\u2019t anything you\u2019re doing wrong, and it settles by around three to four months. Things that can help in the moment are holding, gentle rocking, white noise and winding. Just as important \u2014 look after yourself; if you ever feel overwhelmed, it\u2019s fine to put baby down safely and take a break, and never shake the baby.', b:['Crying in a well, thriving baby','Common, harmless, self-limiting','Not the parent\u2019s fault','Soothing techniques','Parent wellbeing + never shake'] },

  /* ---------- Metabolic ---------- */
  { c:'Obesity', t:'Metabolic', m:'I want to talk about weight in a way that isn\u2019t about blame, because weight is genuinely complex \u2014 biology, hormones, life circumstances and habits all play a part, it\u2019s not simply willpower. Carrying extra weight does raise the risk of things like diabetes, high blood pressure and joint problems, so it\u2019s worth tackling for your health, not appearance. The foundation is sustainable changes to eating and activity, supported by a structured programme. There are also genuinely effective medications now \u2014 the GLP-1 injections \u2014 and for some people surgery, where you\u2019re eligible. Even a 5\u201310% loss makes a real difference. We\u2019ll find what fits your life and go at your pace.', b:['Non-judgemental, complex-condition framing','Health risks not appearance','Lifestyle foundation','Medication/surgery options','Realistic 5\u201310% goal'] },
  { c:'Gestational diabetes', t:'Metabolic', m:'In pregnancy, the hormones that support the baby also make your body less responsive to insulin, so for some women blood sugar rises \u2014 that\u2019s gestational diabetes. It\u2019s common, it\u2019s not your fault, and it usually disappears after the birth. We treat it to keep both you and the baby well, because high sugar can make the baby grow larger. Most women control it with changes to diet and activity, and some need tablets or insulin for a while \u2014 all safe in pregnancy. You\u2019ll have extra monitoring and scans. Afterwards your sugar normally returns to normal, but it does flag a higher future risk of type 2 diabetes, so we\u2019ll keep an eye on it.', b:['Pregnancy hormones + insulin explanation','Common, not your fault, usually temporary','Why we treat (baby growth)','Diet first, then meds/insulin','Future type 2 risk'] },
  { c:'High cholesterol', t:'Metabolic', m:'Cholesterol is a fatty substance your body needs, but too much of the \u201cbad\u201d type can build up inside artery walls over years \u2014 like limescale furring up a pipe \u2014 narrowing them and raising the risk of heart attack and stroke. You won\u2019t feel it happening, which is why we look at your overall risk rather than waiting for symptoms. Diet and exercise help, and where the risk is high enough, a statin tablet lowers it effectively and is one of the best-evidenced medicines we have. The common worries about statins are mostly overstated \u2014 serious side-effects are rare, and we can review if you get muscle aches. It\u2019s about prevention, quietly, over years.', b:['Furring-up-the-pipe analogy','Silent \u2014 treat overall risk','Diet/exercise + statin','Statin reassurance','Prevention framing'] },
  { c:'Osteoporosis', t:'Metabolic', m:'Osteoporosis means the bones have become less dense and more fragile \u2014 the internal honeycomb structure thins, so they can break more easily, sometimes from a minor stumble. It\u2019s silent until a fracture happens, which is why we treat it before that point. The plan is to strengthen the bones and reduce fracture risk: a bone-protecting medicine such as a bisphosphonate, with calcium and vitamin D, plus weight-bearing exercise, stopping smoking and easing alcohol. We also look at preventing falls. Take the bisphosphonate as directed \u2014 upright, with water, before food. Treated well, we genuinely lower the chance of the fractures that affect independence.', b:['Thinning honeycomb/fragile bone analogy','Silent until fracture','Bisphosphonate + calcium/vit D','Exercise + falls prevention','Correct tablet administration'] },
  { c:'Vitamin D deficiency', t:'Metabolic', m:'Vitamin D is made in the skin from sunlight and helps your body absorb calcium to keep bones and muscles healthy. In the UK, especially in winter, with darker skin or staying covered up, it\u2019s very common to run low \u2014 which can cause vague aches, tired muscles and low energy. It\u2019s easily fixed: a course of supplements to top you up, then a regular maintenance dose, particularly over the winter months. It\u2019s not dangerous and it\u2019s very treatable. I\u2019ll usually check it with a blood test and recheck once we\u2019ve replaced it. Most people notice the aches and tiredness ease over a few weeks to months.', b:['Sunlight \u2192 vit D \u2192 calcium/bone explanation','Why common in UK','Symptoms','Replace then maintain','Reassurance + recheck'] },

  /* ---------- Hormones ---------- */
  { c:'Overactive thyroid', t:'Hormones', m:'Your thyroid is the gland in your neck that sets your body\u2019s pace, like an accelerator. Right now it\u2019s producing too much hormone, so everything is running too fast \u2014 that\u2019s the racing heart, weight loss despite eating, tremor, feeling hot, anxious and not sleeping. It\u2019s very treatable. We use tablets to dial the gland back down, sometimes a tablet to settle the racing heart in the meantime, and the specialists may discuss longer-term options. We\u2019ll monitor with blood tests as we adjust. Most people feel much better within weeks. Let me know about any eye symptoms, and come back urgently if you become very unwell with a high fever \u2014 that\u2019s rare but important.', b:['Accelerator/overactive gland analogy','Symptoms linked to \u201ctoo fast\u201d','Tablets + heart-rate control','Blood-test monitoring','Eye/thyroid-storm safety-net'] },
  { c:'Addison\u2019s disease', t:'Hormones', m:'Your adrenal glands, which sit on top of the kidneys, make cortisol \u2014 a hormone your body relies on to handle stress and keep blood pressure and salts balanced. In Addison\u2019s, they don\u2019t make enough, which causes the tiredness, weight loss, dizziness on standing and sometimes darker skin. The treatment is simple and life-changing: we replace the missing hormone with daily tablets, and you feel like yourself again. The crucial part is what to do when you\u2019re ill or stressed \u2014 your body can\u2019t ramp up cortisol itself, so you must increase your dose using \u201csick-day rules,\u201d carry an emergency injection, and wear a medical-alert bracelet. If you\u2019re vomiting and can\u2019t take tablets, that\u2019s an emergency.', b:['Cortisol/adrenal explanation','Symptoms','Replace hormone daily','Sick-day rules + emergency kit','Vomiting = emergency'] },
  { c:'Low testosterone', t:'Men\u2019s health', m:'Testosterone is the main male hormone, and low levels can cause low energy, low sex drive, mood changes and reduced muscle. But I want to be careful here, because tiredness has many causes and low testosterone is actually uncommon and over-blamed \u2014 so rather than just \u201ctopping up,\u201d we work out the real reason. If we do suspect it, we confirm properly with a morning blood test, repeated, plus a few related hormones. Importantly, testosterone is not an energy tonic, and taking it when you don\u2019t need it \u2014 or buying it from the gym \u2014 can cause real harm, including infertility. Let\u2019s find and treat the actual cause first.', b:['What testosterone does','Tiredness over-attributed to low-T','Test correctly (morning, repeated)','Not a tonic; harms incl. infertility','Find the real cause'] },
  { c:'Precocious puberty', t:'Children', m:'Puberty is the normal process of growing up, but in your daughter it has started earlier than expected, before the usual age \u2014 that\u2019s what the breast development and growth spurt are. Most of the time there\u2019s no sinister cause, but it does need proper assessment for two reasons: early puberty can affect final adult height because the bones mature faster, and occasionally there\u2019s an underlying cause worth finding. So I\u2019m referring her to the children\u2019s hormone specialists, who\u2019ll do a bone-age X-ray, some blood tests and a scan if needed. If treatment is the right thing, there\u2019s a medicine that safely pauses puberty until the appropriate age. You were right to bring her.', b:['Early-onset normal process explanation','Usually no sinister cause','Why it matters (height/cause)','Specialist assessment','Treatment can pause puberty'] },

  /* ---------- Mind ---------- */
  { c:'Obsessive-compulsive disorder', t:'Mind', m:'OCD is a recognised, common and very treatable condition \u2014 not a quirk or a weakness. It works as a cycle: an intrusive, unwanted thought spikes your anxiety, and a ritual like checking or washing brings the anxiety down for a moment \u2014 but that relief actually trains the brain to need the ritual more. Those distressing thoughts are the opposite of what you want, which is exactly why they upset you; people with OCD don\u2019t act on them. The most effective treatment is a talking therapy called exposure and response prevention, which breaks the cycle, and a medication \u2014 an SSRI \u2014 often at a higher dose, helps too. This genuinely gets better.', b:['Recognise/destigmatise OCD','Obsession\u2013compulsion cycle','Intrusive thoughts are egodystonic','ERP + SSRI treatment','Instil hope'] },
  { c:'PTSD', t:'Mind', m:'After a frightening or traumatic event, the brain\u2019s alarm system can stay switched on, as if the danger were still present \u2014 that\u2019s why you get flashbacks, nightmares, feeling on edge, and avoiding reminders. It\u2019s a normal response to an abnormal event, not a flaw, and it\u2019s treatable. The most effective treatments are specific talking therapies \u2014 trauma-focused CBT or a technique called EMDR \u2014 which help the brain properly process and \u201cfile away\u201d the memory so it stops intruding. Medication can help alongside. I\u2019ll refer you for that therapy, and we\u2019ll support you in the meantime. How you\u2019re feeling makes complete sense given what you went through.', b:['Stuck alarm-system explanation','Normal response, treatable','Trauma-focused CBT/EMDR','Medication adjunct','Validate the experience'] },
  { c:'Panic disorder', t:'Mind', m:'A panic attack is a surge of the body\u2019s fear response firing when there\u2019s no actual danger \u2014 a false alarm. The racing heart, breathlessness and tingling are real physical effects of that surge, often from over-breathing, which is why it feels so frightening and like something is seriously wrong. But the surge always peaks and passes, and it isn\u2019t dangerous. Understanding that cycle \u2014 fear feeding the physical symptoms feeding more fear \u2014 is half the treatment. A talking therapy, CBT, is very effective, with breathing techniques to use in the moment, and medication if it\u2019s frequent. We\u2019ll check there\u2019s nothing physical too, so the reassurance is solid.', b:['False-alarm fear-response explanation','Physical symptoms are real but harmless','The self-perpetuating cycle','CBT + breathing \u00b1 medication','Exclude physical causes'] },
  { c:'Eating disorder', t:'Mind', m:'An eating disorder isn\u2019t about vanity or willpower \u2014 it\u2019s a serious mental health condition where difficult feelings get tangled up with food, eating and body image, and it can take over and become frightening to live with. The restriction or behaviours feel like control, but they affect both your body and your mind, and there can be real physical risks we need to monitor. The important message is that recovery is genuinely possible with the right support. I\u2019d like to refer you to a specialist eating-disorder service, and we\u2019ll keep you safe physically in the meantime. Thank you for telling me \u2014 that took courage, and you don\u2019t have to manage this alone.', b:['Mental-health condition, not vanity','Feelings tangled with food/body','Physical + psychological risk','Specialist referral; recovery possible','Validate the disclosure'] },
  { c:'Emotionally unstable personality disorder', t:'Mind', m:'This is a pattern \u2014 often rooted in difficult earlier experiences \u2014 where emotions run very intense and change quickly, relationships feel unstable, and distress can become overwhelming, sometimes leading to self-harm. It\u2019s not a character flaw, and the name sounds harsher than it is. The most helpful thing to know is that it responds well to structured talking therapies \u2014 approaches like DBT teach practical skills to ride out intense emotions and stay safe. Medication has a limited role. We\u2019ll work on a crisis plan together for the hardest moments, and I\u2019ll make sure you have support between appointments. Things can and do get better with the right help.', b:['Intense, shifting emotions explanation','Not a character flaw','Structured therapy (DBT)','Crisis plan + support','Hope for improvement'] },
  { c:'Insomnia', t:'Mind', m:'Insomnia is when sleep won\u2019t come or won\u2019t stay, and the frustrating thing is that worrying about sleep keeps you awake \u2014 trying harder backfires. Often the bed has become a place your brain associates with being awake and anxious rather than sleeping. The most effective and lasting treatment isn\u2019t a sleeping tablet \u2014 those help briefly but cause dependence \u2014 it\u2019s a structured approach called CBT for insomnia: things like a fixed wake time, only going to bed when sleepy, getting up if you can\u2019t sleep, and cutting late screens and caffeine. It rebuilds the bed\u2013sleep link. I\u2019ll also check nothing else, like low mood or pain, is driving it.', b:['Trying-too-hard backfires','Bed\u2013wakefulness association','Avoid reliance on sleeping tablets','CBT-for-insomnia measures','Screen underlying causes'] },
  { c:'Bereavement', t:'Mind', m:'What you\u2019re feeling is grief, and grief is not an illness \u2014 it\u2019s the natural, if agonising, response to losing someone who mattered. There\u2019s no right way or fixed timetable to do it, and waves of sadness, anger, guilt or numbness are all normal, even years on. I don\u2019t want to medicalise something human, but I do want to support you through it. Lean on people, be gentle with yourself, and there are bereavement support services I can point you to. I\u2019ll just keep a gentle eye out for grief tipping into a depression that needs more help \u2014 if you\u2019re not coping day to day, or have thoughts of not wanting to be here, please come back.', b:['Grief is normal, not an illness','No timetable/right way','Support without over-medicalising','Signpost bereavement services','Watch for depression/risk'] },
  { c:'Premenstrual dysphoric disorder', t:'Mind', m:'This is not \u201cjust PMS\u201d \u2014 it\u2019s a recognised, severe condition called PMDD, and you\u2019re not going mad. In the week or two before your period your mood crashes severely \u2014 rage, despair, feeling out of control \u2014 and then lifts once your period starts, so you genuinely feel well for part of the month. That on-off, predictable pattern is the key. I\u2019d like you to keep a symptom diary over a couple of cycles to confirm it. The good news is there are effective treatments: an antidepressant (an SSRI) that can be taken either daily or just in those two weeks, a hormonal option, and talking therapy. You\u2019ve carried this alone for too long.', b:['Not \u201cjust PMS\u201d \u2014 validate','Cyclical luteal pattern with relief','Confirm with a diary','SSRI (continuous/luteal) + hormonal/CBT','Reassurance/hope'] },

  /* ---------- Brain & nerves ---------- */
  { c:'Trigeminal neuralgia', t:'Brain & nerves', m:'Those electric-shock, stabbing pains in your face are trigeminal neuralgia \u2014 a nerve that supplies the face misfires, sending brief jolts of severe pain, often triggered by light touch, chewing or even a breeze. It\u2019s not your teeth, even though it can feel like it, and it\u2019s not dangerous \u2014 but it\u2019s exhausting, and it\u2019s treatable. The first-line treatment isn\u2019t a normal painkiller; it\u2019s a tablet called carbamazepine that calms the nerve, and it works well for most people. I\u2019ll start it low and build up, and monitor with blood tests. If it doesn\u2019t settle, the neurologists have further options, including procedures. Stop the tablet and tell me if you get a rash.', b:['Misfiring nerve explanation','Touch/chewing triggers; not dental','Carbamazepine first-line (not normal painkillers)','Titrate + monitor','Neurology if refractory'] },
  { c:'Cluster headache', t:'Brain & nerves', m:'Cluster headache is one of the most severe pains we know, but it\u2019s a specific, recognisable pattern: excruciating pain around one eye, with that eye going red and watery and the nostril blocking, lasting up to a couple of hours, often striking at the same time of day in bouts or \u201cclusters\u201d over weeks. Ordinary painkillers are too slow to help. What does work is high-flow oxygen and a fast-acting injection called sumatriptan to abort an attack, and there are preventive tablets to take during a cluster period. I\u2019ll arrange those and involve the neurologists. It\u2019s not dangerous, but it\u2019s genuinely one of the worst pains, so let\u2019s treat it properly.', b:['Severe one-sided peri-orbital pain + autonomic','Clustering pattern','Oxygen + sumatriptan to abort','Preventers during a cluster','Neurology involvement'] },
  { c:'Tension-type headache', t:'Brain & nerves', m:'This is the most common type of headache \u2014 a tight, band-like pressure around the head, often building through the day, linked to stress, poor sleep, screen time, dehydration or tense neck muscles. The reassuring part is there\u2019s nothing dangerous going on; it\u2019s the muscles and tension, not a sign of something sinister. The trap to avoid is taking painkillers most days \u2014 that paradoxically causes a constant \u201cmedication-overuse\u201d headache of its own. So we focus on the triggers: regular breaks, hydration, sleep, managing stress, and limiting painkillers to a couple of days a week. Come back if the pattern changes, it\u2019s suddenly severe, or you get any new symptoms \u2014 then I\u2019d look further.', b:['Band-like tension explanation','Reassure \u2014 not sinister','Avoid medication-overuse headache','Trigger management','Red-flag safety-net'] },
  { c:'Bell\u2019s palsy', t:'Brain & nerves', m:'Bell\u2019s palsy is a sudden weakness of one side of the face caused by the nerve that controls the facial muscles becoming inflamed and swollen, probably after a viral trigger. It looks alarming \u2014 a drooping face \u2014 but it is not a stroke; the key difference is that here the whole side, including the forehead, is affected. Most people recover well over weeks to months. A short course of steroid tablets, started early, improves recovery. The one thing we must protect is the eye on that side, because you can\u2019t blink fully \u2014 so use lubricating drops and tape it shut at night. If you have other weakness, slurred speech or arm/leg symptoms, that\u2019s different \u2014 call 999.', b:['Inflamed facial nerve explanation','Whole side incl. forehead (not stroke)','Early steroids improve recovery','Protect the eye','Stroke red flags = 999'] },
  { c:'Epilepsy', t:'Brain & nerves', m:'A seizure happens when there\u2019s a sudden burst of abnormal electrical activity in the brain \u2014 like a brief electrical storm \u2014 and epilepsy means a tendency to have these recurrently. Daily anti-seizure medication greatly reduces or stops them for most people, and the most important thing is taking it consistently, because missing doses is a common trigger. We\u2019ll also look at other triggers like lack of sleep and alcohol. Two practical things we must discuss: driving and the DVLA rules, and some safety advice around swimming and heights. If a seizure lasts more than five minutes, or one follows another without recovery, that\u2019s an emergency \u2014 call 999.', b:['Electrical-storm analogy','Consistent medication is key','Trigger avoidance','Driving/DVLA + safety advice','Status epilepticus = 999'] },
  { c:'Parkinson\u2019s disease', t:'Brain & nerves', m:'Parkinson\u2019s happens because cells deep in the brain that make a chemical messenger called dopamine \u2014 which helps control movement \u2014 gradually reduce. Less dopamine causes the slowness, stiffness, and the tremor that\u2019s typically worse at rest. It\u2019s a long-term condition, but a very manageable one: medication replaces or boosts that dopamine and can control symptoms well for years, looked after by the specialists alongside us. It progresses slowly, and there\u2019s a lot of support \u2014 physiotherapy, Parkinson\u2019s nurses, and help with day-to-day living. We\u2019ll go at your pace and answer questions as they come. Many people live full, active lives for a long time after diagnosis.', b:['Dopamine-loss explanation','Slowness/stiffness/rest tremor','Dopamine medication + specialist','Slow progression + support','Realistic, hopeful framing'] },
  { c:'Alzheimer\u2019s dementia', t:'Brain & nerves', m:'Dementia is a gradual decline in memory and thinking caused by changes in the brain \u2014 in Alzheimer\u2019s, the connections between brain cells slowly break down, which is why recent memory tends to go first while older memories and personality are preserved longer. I know this is a frightening word, so let me be clear about what helps: there are medications that can ease symptoms for a time, and a great deal of support \u2014 memory services, practical aids, and help for you and the family. Planning ahead while things are clearer \u2014 wishes, affairs, support \u2014 is empowering, not gloomy. We\u2019ll walk this with you, and you won\u2019t be managing it alone.', b:['Breaking brain-cell connections explanation','Recent memory first','Medication eases symptoms','Memory services + family support','Forward planning + non-abandonment'] },
  { c:'Multiple sclerosis', t:'Brain & nerves', m:'Multiple sclerosis is a condition where the immune system mistakenly attacks the protective coating around the nerves \u2014 like damage to the insulation on an electrical wire \u2014 so messages between the brain and body get disrupted. That\u2019s why symptoms can be so varied: vision changes, numbness, weakness or balance problems, often coming and going in episodes. It\u2019s confirmed by the neurologists with scans. The encouraging news is that modern treatments can significantly reduce relapses and protect the future, and there\u2019s strong support for managing symptoms. I\u2019ll refer you urgently to neurology. There\u2019s a lot of uncertainty at first, which is hard \u2014 we\u2019ll take it step by step and keep you supported throughout.', b:['Nerve-insulation/wiring analogy','Varied, relapsing symptoms','Neurology + scans confirm','Treatments reduce relapses','Support through uncertainty'] },
  { c:'Peripheral neuropathy', t:'Brain & nerves', m:'The tingling, numbness and burning in your feet is peripheral neuropathy \u2014 the small nerves that carry sensation from your feet to the brain have become damaged, so they send faulty signals. It usually starts in the toes and creeps up, in a \u201cstocking\u201d pattern. The key job is finding the cause, because many are treatable \u2014 most commonly diabetes, but also low B12, thyroid, alcohol and some medicines \u2014 so I\u2019ll do some blood tests. We treat the underlying cause where we can, protect the feet (because reduced sensation risks unnoticed injuries), and use specific nerve-pain medicines if it\u2019s painful. Ordinary painkillers don\u2019t work well for this kind of pain.', b:['Damaged sensory nerves explanation','Stocking distribution','Find the cause (bloods)','Foot protection','Nerve-specific pain treatment'] },
  { c:'Restless legs syndrome', t:'Brain & nerves', m:'Restless legs is an irresistible urge to move your legs, with an unpleasant crawling sensation that\u2019s worse when you\u2019re resting in the evening and eases when you move \u2014 which is exactly why it wrecks your sleep. It\u2019s a genuine neurological condition, not \u201call in the mind.\u201d One really important and treatable cause is low iron, so I\u2019ll check that and top it up if needed, which often helps a lot. We\u2019ll also look at things that worsen it \u2014 caffeine, some medicines \u2014 and simple measures like exercise and good sleep habits. If it\u2019s severe and stubborn, there are specific tablets, though we choose carefully, especially in pregnancy.', b:['Urge-to-move, evening, relieved-by-movement','Genuine condition','Check/treat iron','Caffeine/medication triggers','Cautious medication if severe'] },
  { c:'Carpal tunnel syndrome', t:'Brain & nerves', m:'Carpal tunnel syndrome is a pinched nerve at the wrist. A nerve passes through a narrow tunnel there, and when the tunnel gets crowded the nerve is squeezed \u2014 causing the tingling, numbness and pain in the thumb side of the hand, classically waking you at night and easing when you shake the hand. It\u2019s common, and often linked to repetitive use, pregnancy or things like an underactive thyroid. Many cases settle with a wrist splint worn at night to keep the wrist straight, and we can treat any underlying cause. If it\u2019s persistent or the muscles weaken, a steroid injection or a small operation to release the tunnel is very effective.', b:['Pinched nerve in a tunnel analogy','Thumb-side, night, shake-relief','Common associations','Night splint first-line','Injection/surgery if persistent'] },
  { c:'Postherpetic neuralgia', t:'Brain & nerves', m:'This is nerve pain left behind after shingles. The shingles virus damaged a nerve, and even though the rash has gone, that nerve keeps firing pain signals \u2014 which is why the skin still burns and stings, and even clothing touching it hurts. It\u2019s a recognised after-effect, not a sign of something new. Ordinary painkillers don\u2019t work well for nerve pain, so we use specific nerve medicines \u2014 like amitriptyline or gabapentin \u2014 started low and built up, plus numbing patches for the skin. It can take time and patience, and it does tend to improve. For the future, the shingles vaccine lowers the chance of this happening again.', b:['Damaged nerve still firing','Burning skin/allodynia, rash gone','Nerve-specific medicines, not normal painkillers','Patches + patience','Shingles vaccine prevention'] },
  { c:'Essential tremor', t:'Brain & nerves', m:'Essential tremor is a common, benign shaking \u2014 usually of the hands \u2014 that shows up when you\u2019re using them, like holding a cup or writing, and often runs in families. The key reassurance is that it\u2019s not Parkinson\u2019s: Parkinson\u2019s tremor is worse at rest, whereas yours appears with action, and there\u2019s no slowness or stiffness. Many people don\u2019t need treatment if it\u2019s mild. If it\u2019s affecting daily life, there are tablets \u2014 such as propranolol \u2014 that can reduce it. Interestingly, alcohol often calms it temporarily, which can be a clue, though it\u2019s not a treatment. If anything changes or other symptoms appear, come back and we\u2019ll reassess.', b:['Benign action tremor explanation','Distinguish from Parkinson\u2019s','Often familial','Treat only if affecting life (propranolol)','Reassurance + review'] },
  { c:'Motor neurone disease', t:'Brain & nerves', m:'I want to be honest and careful with you. Your symptoms \u2014 progressive weakness without pain, the speech and the muscle twitching \u2014 are significant, and I can\u2019t give you a firm diagnosis here today. They need an urgent specialist assessment, because one of the conditions affecting the nerves that control muscles, called motor neurone disease, is something the neurologists will look at and rule in or out. I don\u2019t want to alarm you or falsely reassure you \u2014 that\u2019s exactly why I\u2019m referring you quickly, so you get answers and, whatever it turns out to be, the right support from the start. I\u2019m here, and we\u2019ll go through whatever they find together.', b:['Honest, careful framing','Progressive painless weakness is significant','Urgent neurology, no premature label','Avoid false reassurance','Non-abandonment'] },
  { c:'Narcolepsy', t:'Brain & nerves', m:'Narcolepsy is a real neurological sleep condition \u2014 you are not lazy. The brain struggles to regulate the boundary between sleep and wake, so you\u2019re overwhelmingly sleepy in the day and can fall asleep suddenly, and the dividing line blurs \u2014 hence the dream-like states and the paralysis as you drop off. That muscle weakness when you laugh strongly is called cataplexy, and it\u2019s quite specific to narcolepsy. The sleep specialists confirm it with sleep studies. It\u2019s manageable: scheduled naps, good sleep habits, a wake-promoting medicine for the sleepiness, and treatment for the cataplexy. We do need to talk about driving safety and the DVLA. It has a big impact, and it deserves proper help.', b:['Real condition, not laziness','Sleep\u2013wake boundary explanation','Cataplexy clue','Sleep study + treatment','Driving/DVLA'] },

  /* ---------- Bones & joints ---------- */
  { c:'Rheumatoid arthritis', t:'Bones & joints', m:'Rheumatoid arthritis is different from \u201cwear and tear\u201d arthritis \u2014 here the immune system mistakenly attacks the joint linings, causing inflammation. That\u2019s why the small joints of the hands and feet are swollen, painful and especially stiff first thing in the morning for over an hour. Catching it early really matters, because modern medicines that calm the immune attack can prevent lasting joint damage \u2014 so I\u2019m referring you urgently to rheumatology. These \u201cdisease-modifying\u201d drugs have transformed the outlook; many people stay active with little damage. We\u2019ll manage symptoms in the meantime. It\u2019s a long-term condition, but a very treatable one when we act promptly.', b:['Immune attack vs wear-and-tear','Small joints, morning stiffness >1hr','Early treatment prevents damage','Urgent rheumatology + DMARDs','Hopeful outlook'] },
  { c:'Plantar fasciitis', t:'Bones & joints', m:'Plantar fasciitis is the commonest cause of heel pain. There\u2019s a band of tissue along the sole, and where it attaches to the heel it gets strained and irritated \u2014 which is why the pain is worst on those first few steps in the morning or after sitting, then eases as you warm up. It\u2019s harmless but can be stubborn. The mainstays are stretching the calf and the sole, supportive cushioned footwear or insoles, easing back aggravating activity, and anti-inflammatories. I\u2019ll be honest \u2014 it can take a few months to settle, but it does, and most people don\u2019t need anything more. If it\u2019s really persistent, physiotherapy and other options help.', b:['First-step heel pain explanation','Harmless but stubborn','Stretching + supportive footwear','Realistic (months) timeline','Physio if persistent'] },
  { c:'Tennis elbow', t:'Bones & joints', m:'Tennis elbow is an overuse strain of the tendons on the outer side of the elbow, where the muscles that pull the wrist back attach \u2014 which is why it hurts to grip, lift or shake hands. It usually comes from repetitive forearm use, not a single injury. It\u2019s not serious and it does settle, though it can be slow. The treatment that genuinely works is a progressive strengthening programme with physiotherapy, along with easing the aggravating activity, a forearm strap and anti-inflammatory gel. I\u2019d avoid steroid injections as a first move \u2014 they help short-term but can slow long-term recovery. Be patient with the exercises; that\u2019s the path to getting better.', b:['Overuse tendon strain explanation','Gripping/lifting pain','Progressive loading physio','Avoid early steroid injection','Realistic timeline'] },
  { c:'Frozen shoulder', t:'Bones & joints', m:'Frozen shoulder is exactly what it sounds like \u2014 the lining of the shoulder joint becomes inflamed and tight, so the joint stiffens and becomes painful, and you can\u2019t reach behind your back or overhead. A telltale sign is that movement is limited whether you move it yourself or I move it for you. It\u2019s commoner in people with diabetes. It goes through stages \u2014 painful, then stiff, then gradually thawing \u2014 and I\u2019ll be honest, recovery is slow, often one to three years, but it does get better. We help it along with painkillers, physiotherapy to keep movement, and a steroid injection in the painful stage, plus keeping any diabetes well controlled.', b:['Inflamed/tight capsule explanation','Active + passive both limited','Diabetes link','Slow phased recovery','Physio + steroid injection'] },
  { c:'De Quervain\u2019s tenosynovitis', t:'Bones & joints', m:'This is inflammation of the tendons on the thumb side of your wrist \u2014 very common in new mothers, because lifting and scooping the baby strains exactly those tendons. That\u2019s why it hurts to lift, grip or move the thumb, and there\u2019s tenderness and swelling there. It\u2019s not dangerous, and it usually settles well. The mainstays are resting the thumb with a splint, changing how you lift \u2014 scooping with your forearms rather than spreading the thumb \u2014 and anti-inflammatories that are fine with breastfeeding. If it doesn\u2019t settle, a small steroid injection works very well, and very occasionally a minor operation. Let\u2019s start with the splint and technique.', b:['Thumb-side tendon strain explanation','New-mother lifting cause','Splint + technique change','Breastfeeding-safe analgesia','Injection if persistent'] },
  { c:'Achilles tendinopathy', t:'Bones & joints', m:'This is an overuse problem of the Achilles tendon \u2014 the big cord at the back of the ankle \u2014 which has become irritated and thickened, often after upping your running or training. That\u2019s why it\u2019s stiff and sore first thing and when you start activity, with a tender lump on the tendon. The treatment that genuinely works is a gradual strengthening programme with specific loading exercises, guided by a physiotherapist, while easing back rather than stopping completely. I\u2019d avoid a steroid injection into the tendon, because it raises the risk of it rupturing. It can take a few months. One quick check \u2014 if you ever feel a sudden pop and can\u2019t push off, that needs urgent assessment.', b:['Overuse tendon explanation','Start-of-activity stiffness','Progressive loading physio','Avoid steroid injection (rupture)','Sudden rupture safety-net'] },
  { c:'Mechanical back pain', t:'Bones & joints', m:'Most back pain like yours is mechanical \u2014 it comes from the muscles, ligaments and joints of the back rather than anything sinister, and the reassuring fact is that scans usually aren\u2019t needed and often show harmless changes anyway. The single most important message is to keep moving and stay active \u2014 rest and fear make it worse, whereas gentle movement and getting back to normal activity is what helps it recover, alongside simple painkillers. Most settles within a few weeks. I\u2019ve checked for warning signs and there are none. But do come back urgently if you get numbness around the back passage, trouble passing urine, or weakness in the legs \u2014 those are different and need same-day assessment.', b:['Mechanical, not sinister','Scans usually unnecessary','Keep active \u2014 don\u2019t rest','Most settles in weeks','Cauda equina red flags'] },
  { c:'Costochondritis', t:'Bones & joints', m:'I know chest pain is frightening, so let me reassure you properly \u2014 having checked your heart and the serious causes. This is costochondritis: inflammation of the joints where the ribs meet the breastbone. The giveaway is that the pain is sharp, in one spot, worse when you breathe deeply or move, and \u2014 crucially \u2014 I can reproduce it by pressing on the ribcage. It\u2019s harmless and settles over a few weeks, helped by anti-inflammatory painkillers and easing aggravating movements. Because I\u2019ve taken it seriously and ruled out the heart and lungs, this reassurance is solid. But do seek urgent help for central, crushing or exertional chest pain, breathlessness or sweating \u2014 anything unlike this.', b:['Reassure after excluding serious','Rib-joint inflammation, reproducible','Harmless, self-limiting','Anti-inflammatories','Cardiac red-flag safety-net'] },
  { c:'Joint hypermobility', t:'Bones & joints', m:'Being very flexible \u2014 \u201cdouble-jointed\u201d \u2014 comes from your ligaments being more stretchy than usual, and for some people that causes real problems: joints that partly dislocate and ache, easy bruising, fatigue, and sometimes dizziness or tummy symptoms, because it can affect more than just the joints. I\u2019m sorry if you\u2019ve been brushed off before \u2014 this is real. The cornerstone of management is physiotherapy to strengthen and stabilise the joints and improve control, with pacing to avoid flares, and we\u2019ll address the pain sensibly and the other symptoms too. I\u2019ll also check there are no features of the rarer, more serious types that need the specialists. You deserve a proper, joined-up plan.', b:['Stretchy ligaments + multisystem explanation','Validate (not dismissed)','Physio cornerstone','Manage pain/other symptoms','Screen serious subtypes'] },

  /* ---------- Skin ---------- */
  { c:'Psoriasis', t:'Skin', m:'Psoriasis is a condition where skin cells are made far too quickly \u2014 your body renews skin in days instead of weeks, so cells pile up faster than they shed, forming those thick, red, scaly patches, often on the elbows, knees and scalp. It\u2019s driven by an overactive immune signal; it\u2019s not contagious and it\u2019s nobody\u2019s fault. It tends to come and go, flaring with stress, infections or some medicines. We treat it with creams \u2014 moisturisers plus specific ones containing vitamin D and steroid \u2014 and for more extensive disease there\u2019s light therapy and tablets via dermatology. One thing I\u2019ll ask about is your joints, because psoriasis can sometimes affect those too.', b:['Fast skin-cell turnover explanation','Immune-driven, not contagious','Flaring triggers','Topical treatments \u2192 specialist options','Ask about joints (psoriatic arthritis)'] },
  { c:'Lichen planus', t:'Skin', m:'This is lichen planus \u2014 the itchy, flat-topped purple bumps with fine white lines, and the lacy white pattern inside your mouth, are typical. It\u2019s thought to be the immune system reacting against the skin; it\u2019s not cancer and it\u2019s not contagious. The skin version usually fades over several months, sometimes leaving a brownish mark for a while, and a strong steroid cream settles the itch. The mouth version can be more persistent. One reason I\u2019ll keep an eye on the mouth: long-standing sore, raw patches there carry a small risk of change over time, so I\u2019d like your dentist to review it periodically \u2014 sensible monitoring, nothing to panic about. I\u2019ll also check your medicines, as some can trigger it.', b:['Itchy violaceous bumps + oral lacy pattern','Immune, not cancer/contagious','Potent topical steroid; self-limiting skin','Oral monitoring (small SCC risk)','Review drug triggers'] },
  { c:'Pityriasis rosea', t:'Skin', m:'Good news \u2014 this isn\u2019t ringworm spreading. That first larger oval patch is a \u201cherald patch,\u201d and the smaller oval ones following the lines of your skin are the classic pattern of pityriasis rosea, a harmless rash that often follows a mild viral illness. It clears up entirely on its own over about six to twelve weeks, it\u2019s not really contagious, and it may leave faint marks for a while that also fade. You don\u2019t need an antifungal cream \u2014 that wouldn\u2019t help. For the itch, a good moisturiser, a mild steroid cream and an antihistamine are all you need. Come back if it spreads to your palms and soles or you feel unwell, so I can reconsider.', b:['Not ringworm \u2014 herald patch + Christmas-tree','Often post-viral, self-limiting','Resolves in 6\u201312 weeks','Symptomatic itch care, no antifungal','Safety-net atypical features'] },
  { c:'Molluscum contagiosum', t:'Skin', m:'Those little pearly bumps with a tiny dimple in the middle are molluscum \u2014 a very common, harmless viral skin infection in children. The reassuring and slightly frustrating news is that they clear up completely on their own, usually within a year or so, without scarring. Because of that, we generally don\u2019t actively treat them in healthy children \u2014 freezing or scraping them can be painful and can scar, whereas time does the job kindly. He doesn\u2019t need to stay off school or swimming \u2014 just cover them if you like and try to stop scratching, which spreads them. If that surrounding skin gets eczema-y, a moisturiser and mild steroid cream will settle the itch.', b:['Pearly umbilicated viral bumps','Harmless, self-limiting (no scarring)','Avoid harsh treatment in children','No school/swimming exclusion','Manage surrounding eczema'] },
  { c:'Athlete\u2019s foot', t:'Skin', m:'Athlete\u2019s foot is a fungal infection of the skin, very common with sweaty, enclosed footwear and gyms \u2014 the warm, damp environment between the toes is exactly what the fungus likes, hence the itchy, flaky, soggy, cracked skin and odour. An antifungal cream, used properly and continued a little beyond clearing, sorts the skin. Just as important is keeping the cause at bay: dry carefully between the toes, change socks, let shoes air, use antifungal powder, and wear flip-flops in communal showers. If it keeps coming back, the nails can be a hidden reservoir \u2014 we\u2019d check those, as they often need a course of tablets. And in diabetes, foot care matters more, so keep an eye for spreading infection.', b:['Fungal infection + damp environment','Antifungal cream (continue beyond clearing)','Keep-dry/hygiene measures','Nail reservoir for recurrence','Diabetic cellulitis caveat'] },
  { c:'Head lice', t:'Skin', m:'First, please don\u2019t be embarrassed \u2014 head lice have nothing to do with cleanliness; they actually like clean hair, and any child can get them. They spread by heads touching, and they can\u2019t jump or fly. The important points: we only treat if we find live lice, so it\u2019s worth confirming with wet combing rather than treating on an itch alone. If there are live lice, everyone in the house with them is treated together \u2014 with a lotion like dimeticone or systematic wet combing \u2014 and crucially repeated after a week to catch any that hatch. There\u2019s no need to keep her off school. Treating just one person, or skipping the repeat, is why they keep coming back.', b:['De-stigmatise (not about hygiene)','Confirm live lice (wet combing)','Treat the whole household + repeat at 1 week','No school exclusion','Why recurrence happens'] },
  { c:'Scabies', t:'Skin', m:'Scabies is an intensely itchy rash caused by a tiny mite that burrows into the skin \u2014 the itch is your body reacting to it, and it\u2019s typically worst at night, with little tracks and spots in the finger webs, wrists and other warm folds. It\u2019s passed by close, prolonged skin contact, so it spreads within households and partners. The treatment is a cream or lotion applied to the whole body from the neck down \u2014 not just the rash \u2014 left on as directed and repeated after a week, and everyone in close contact must be treated at the same time, even if they\u2019re not itchy yet. Wash bedding and clothes hot. The itch can persist for a couple of weeks after successful treatment \u2014 that\u2019s normal.', b:['Burrowing mite + reaction explanation','Night itch, finger-web distribution','Whole-body treatment + repeat','Treat all close contacts together','Itch lingers after cure'] },
  { c:'Acne', t:'Skin', m:'Acne happens when the skin\u2019s oil glands become overactive and the pores get blocked, and bacteria and inflammation do the rest \u2014 giving blackheads, whiteheads and the red, sometimes painful spots. It\u2019s hormonal and incredibly common; it\u2019s not about being unclean, and scrubbing actually makes it worse. We treat it in steps depending on severity: gentle skincare and a topical treatment like benzoyl peroxide or a retinoid to begin, adding antibiotics \u2014 on the skin or as tablets \u2014 or a hormonal option if needed, and the dermatologists have stronger treatments for severe or scarring acne. The key is patience: treatments take six to eight weeks to work, and consistency matters more than intensity.', b:['Oil/blockage/inflammation explanation','Hormonal, common, not about hygiene','Stepwise topical \u2192 systemic','Specialist for severe/scarring','Patience \u2014 6\u20138 weeks'] },
  { c:'Chronic urticaria', t:'Skin', m:'These itchy raised weals are urticaria \u2014 hives. Each individual weal comes up and fades within a day, leaving no mark, often with some lip or eyelid swelling. The frustrating truth is that in most long-lasting cases there\u2019s no specific allergy or food behind it \u2014 the body just releases histamine for months, then it settles \u2014 so you can stop the exhausting hunt for a trigger, and allergy testing usually isn\u2019t helpful. The key treatment is a non-drowsy antihistamine taken every day, not just when you flare, and we can safely increase the dose well above the standard if needed. One safety point: if your tongue or throat ever swells or you struggle to breathe, that\u2019s an emergency \u2014 call 999.', b:['Hives explanation; weals <24h','Usually no allergy \u2014 stop the trigger-hunt','Regular (not PRN) antihistamine, up-titrated','Refer if refractory','Angioedema/airway 999'] },
  { c:'Hyperhidrosis', t:'Skin', m:'Excessive sweating like this \u2014 hands, underarms or feet, even when you\u2019re not hot \u2014 is a recognised medical condition called hyperhidrosis, not a hygiene problem or you being \u201csweaty.\u201d The sweat glands are simply over-active. It\u2019s treatable in steps: we start with a strong aluminium-chloride antiperspirant applied at night, and if that\u2019s not enough there are good options \u2014 a treatment called iontophoresis for the hands, creams or tablets that reduce sweating, and Botox injections, which work very well for the underarms. I can hear how much it affects your confidence and work, and that\u2019s exactly why it\u2019s worth treating properly. I\u2019ll just check the sweating is localised rather than all over, which would prompt a few tests.', b:['Recognised condition, not hygiene','Over-active sweat glands','Stepwise: antiperspirant \u2192 iontophoresis/Botox','Acknowledge the impact','Screen for secondary (generalised) sweating'] },
  { c:'Shingles', t:'Skin', m:'Shingles is the chickenpox virus, which has lain dormant in a nerve since childhood, reactivating \u2014 which is why the painful, blistering rash appears in a band on just one side of the body, following that nerve. It\u2019s the same virus, so someone who\u2019s never had chickenpox could catch chickenpox (not shingles) from the blisters until they crust. An antiviral tablet, started within the first few days, reduces severity and the risk of lingering nerve pain, so timing matters \u2014 plus painkillers. Keep the rash covered. Seek urgent help if it\u2019s near the eye, you\u2019re very unwell, or your immune system is weakened. For the future, there\u2019s a shingles vaccine for eligible older adults.', b:['Reactivated dormant virus explanation','One-sided band; contagious as chickenpox','Early antiviral reduces nerve pain','Eye/immunocompromised red flags','Vaccine note'] },
  { c:'Basal cell carcinoma', t:'Skin', m:'I want to be straight but reassuring. This looks like a basal cell carcinoma \u2014 the commonest type of skin cancer, usually caused by years of sun exposure. The important reassurance is that it\u2019s a very slow-growing, local cancer: it grows in place and essentially never spreads to other parts of the body, so it\u2019s not life-threatening. But it won\u2019t heal on its own and will slowly enlarge, so it does need treating, usually with a minor operation to remove it, which is curative. I\u2019ll refer you to dermatology. Going forward, sun protection \u2014 hat and high-factor cream \u2014 helps prevent more, and it\u2019s worth keeping an eye on your skin for any new non-healing spots.', b:['Commonest skin cancer, sun-related','Reassure \u2014 local, doesn\u2019t spread','Needs treating (won\u2019t self-heal)','Minor excision is curative','Sun protection + surveillance'] },
  { c:'Male-pattern hair loss', t:'Skin', m:'What you\u2019ve got is male-pattern hair loss \u2014 the gradual, patterned thinning that\u2019s genetic and incredibly common; it\u2019s not a sign of any illness. Let me be honest about what works, since you asked. Two treatments have real evidence: a solution called minoxidil you put on the scalp, and a tablet called finasteride. They slow the loss and can thicken things a bit, but they take a few months, work best started early, and only keep working while you use them. Most of the shampoos, vitamins and \u201cgrowth\u201d products have little good evidence. There\u2019s no wrong choice \u2014 treat it, go cosmetic, or accept it \u2014 and I\u2019ll support whatever you decide, and how it\u2019s affecting you matters too.', b:['Genetic patterned loss, not illness','Honest: minoxidil + finasteride work','Realistic limits/ongoing use','Most products are marketing','Support choice + emotional impact'] },

  /* ---------- Infections ---------- */
  { c:'Lyme disease', t:'Infections', m:'That spreading, ring-shaped rash after your woodland trip is the classic sign of early Lyme disease, caught from a tick bite \u2014 even if you never noticed the tick. It\u2019s different from ringworm, which is itchy and scaly; this rash spreads outwards and usually doesn\u2019t itch. The good news is that caught early it treats very well with a course of antibiotics, and importantly I don\u2019t need to wait for a blood test \u2014 early tests can be falsely negative, and the rash itself is enough to diagnose and treat. Most people are fine afterwards. Watch for and tell me urgently about a droopy face, severe headache, palpitations or a swollen joint \u2014 signs it has spread. And cover up against ticks in future.', b:['Erythema migrans after tick bite','Not ringworm (non-itchy, spreading)','Treat clinically, don\u2019t wait for serology','Antibiotic course','Disseminated red flags + prevention'] },
  { c:'Glandular fever', t:'Infections', m:'This is glandular fever, a viral infection (usually the EBV virus) that\u2019s very common in your age group \u2014 which explains the long, severe sore throat, the swollen neck glands and that profound exhaustion. Because it\u2019s viral, antibiotics won\u2019t help, and there\u2019s a specific one \u2014 amoxicillin \u2014 I\u2019d avoid, because it causes a dramatic rash in glandular fever. The main treatment is rest, fluids and painkillers. One important thing: it can swell the spleen, so avoid contact sports and heavy lifting for at least three to four weeks, and get urgent help for sudden severe tummy pain. Be kind to yourself \u2014 the throat eases in a week or two, but the tiredness can linger for several weeks.', b:['EBV viral infection explanation','Viral \u2014 antibiotics won\u2019t help','Avoid amoxicillin (rash)','Spleen/contact-sport advice','Slow fatigue recovery'] },
  { c:'Cellulitis', t:'Infections', m:'Cellulitis is a bacterial infection of the skin and the tissue just beneath it \u2014 bacteria have got in, often through a small crack or break, and are spreading, which is why the area is red, hot, swollen and tender, sometimes with a fever. It\u2019s treated with a course of antibiotics, usually tablets, and it\u2019s helpful to elevate the limb and mark the edge of the redness so we can track it. Most cases improve within a couple of days of starting treatment. But it can occasionally become serious, so come back urgently \u2014 or to A&E \u2014 if the redness spreads quickly, you become feverish and unwell, blisters form, or you feel much worse, as that can need hospital treatment.', b:['Bacterial skin/soft-tissue infection','Entry point + spreading redness','Antibiotics + elevation + mark the edge','Improves in ~48h','Deterioration safety-net'] },
  { c:'Genital herpes', t:'Infections', m:'First, please don\u2019t be embarrassed, and let me say clearly \u2014 this does not mean you\u2019re \u201cdirty.\u201d Genital herpes is extremely common and very manageable. It\u2019s a viral infection; the painful blisters and ulcers and the stinging are this first episode, which is usually the worst one. An antiviral tablet started early settles it faster, and salt baths, painkillers and a numbing gel for weeing help. Honestly: the virus stays in the body so it can recur, but recurrences are usually much milder and shorter, and often become less frequent over time. It can pass on even without visible sores, so condoms reduce the risk. If you\u2019re ever pregnant, mention it. If you can\u2019t pass urine at all, contact us urgently.', b:['Common, manageable \u2014 destigmatise','First episode is the worst','Early antiviral + symptom relief','Recurrences milder; transmission/condoms','Pregnancy + urinary-retention notes'] },
  { c:'Threadworm', t:'Infections', m:'These are threadworms \u2014 incredibly common in children, and, crucially, not a sign that you\u2019re not clean. That night-time bottom itch and the tiny white threads are the giveaway. They spread easily \u2014 scratching puts microscopic eggs on the fingers, which then reach the mouth and others \u2014 which is why the whole family keeps catching it. So the key is to treat everyone in the house together with a single dose of a worm medicine called mebendazole, then a second dose two weeks later to catch any that hatch. Alongside, for two weeks: hot-wash bedding and nightwear, shower in the morning, scrub hands and nails, and keep nails short. Treating just one person is why it returns.', b:['De-stigmatise (not about cleanliness)','Faeco-oral spread explanation','Treat whole household + repeat at 2 weeks','Hygiene measures','Why recurrence happens'] },

  /* ---------- Kidneys & urology ---------- */
  { c:'Acute kidney injury', t:'Kidneys', m:'Your blood test shows your kidneys aren\u2019t filtering as well as usual at the moment \u2014 that\u2019s an acute kidney injury, which sounds dramatic but often means the kidneys are temporarily struggling rather than permanently damaged. Common causes are dehydration, an infection, or sometimes medicines that the kidneys don\u2019t like when you\u2019re unwell. The plan is to find and fix the cause: making sure you\u2019re well hydrated, treating any infection, and pausing certain tablets for now \u2014 I\u2019ll tell you which \u2014 then rechecking the blood. Most cases recover fully. It\u2019s important to keep your fluids up and avoid anti-inflammatory painkillers while this settles. Seek help if you\u2019re passing very little urine or becoming very unwell.', b:['Kidneys temporarily struggling explanation','Common reversible causes','Hydrate + treat cause + pause culprit drugs','Recheck; usually recovers','Avoid NSAIDs; safety-net'] },
  { c:'Prostatitis', t:'Kidneys', m:'Prostatitis is inflammation, often infection, of the prostate \u2014 the small gland that sits below the bladder \u2014 which is why you\u2019ve got that deep pain around the base, pain passing urine, going frequently, and feeling generally unwell. It needs a longer course of antibiotics than a simple water infection, because the prostate is harder for antibiotics to penetrate, often a couple of weeks, plus painkillers and plenty of fluids. Most men improve steadily. Some develop a more lingering, non-infective form, which we manage differently. Seek urgent help if you can\u2019t pass urine at all, develop a high fever with shaking, or feel very unwell \u2014 occasionally it needs hospital treatment.', b:['Prostate inflammation/infection explanation','Symptoms','Longer antibiotic course (penetration)','Fluids/analgesia; chronic form differs','Retention/sepsis red flags'] },
  { c:'Overactive bladder', t:'Kidneys', m:'An overactive bladder means the bladder muscle squeezes when it shouldn\u2019t \u2014 giving you that sudden, urgent need to go, often frequently and sometimes leaking before you reach the toilet. It\u2019s common and not dangerous, but it\u2019s disruptive, and it\u2019s very treatable. We usually start without tablets: a bladder diary to see the pattern, cutting back on caffeine and fizzy drinks, sensible fluid timing, and bladder-training to gradually stretch the time between visits, plus pelvic-floor exercises. If that\u2019s not enough, there are tablets that calm the bladder muscle. I\u2019ll just check your urine first to rule out an infection. Most people get good control with this stepwise approach.', b:['Bladder muscle over-contracting explanation','Common, treatable, not dangerous','Diary + caffeine + bladder training first','Medication if needed','Exclude infection'] },
  { c:'Kidney stones', t:'Kidneys', m:'That severe, gripping pain in your side spreading to the groin, with blood in the urine, is very likely a kidney stone \u2014 a small hard crystal that\u2019s formed in the kidney and is now moving down the tube to the bladder, which is why the pain comes in waves and you can\u2019t get comfortable. The first priority is pain relief \u2014 a strong anti-inflammatory works best \u2014 and I\u2019ll arrange an urgent scan to confirm it and check it isn\u2019t blocking the kidney. Many small stones pass on their own with fluids and time. But seek urgent help if you develop a fever or shivering, the pain can\u2019t be controlled, or you stop passing urine \u2014 a blocked, infected kidney is an emergency.', b:['Stone moving down the tube explanation','Colicky loin-to-groin + haematuria','NSAID pain relief + urgent scan','Small stones pass; hydration','Fever/obstruction emergency'] },
  { c:'Undescended testis', t:'Children', m:'At the baby check we\u2019ve noticed one testicle isn\u2019t sitting in the scrotum \u2014 this is common and very treatable, so let me reassure you. In many baby boys it simply comes down on its own in the first few months. If it hasn\u2019t descended by around three months, I\u2019ll refer him for a small operation called orchidopexy, which places and fixes it in the right spot \u2014 ideally done between about six and twelve months, because the timing helps protect his future fertility. Leaving a testicle undescended long-term can affect fertility and slightly raises a future risk, which is exactly why we treat it in good time. He\u2019s otherwise well, and the outlook with timely surgery is good. You did the right thing.', b:['Common, treatable explanation','Many descend by ~3 months','Orchidopexy ~6\u201312 months for fertility','Why timing matters','Reassurance'] },
  { c:'Balanitis', t:'Men\u2019s health', m:'Balanitis is inflammation of the head of the penis, often with soreness, redness, itch and sometimes discharge. The commonest cause is a thrush (yeast) infection, irritation, or hygiene-related, and it usually responds well to an antifungal cream and gentle washing \u2014 avoiding harsh soaps and drying properly. One important point: because it keeps recurring, I want to check your blood sugar, as recurrent thrush like this can be linked to diabetes and is occasionally the first sign. I\u2019ll also look for a skin condition that can cause scarring and tightening of the foreskin, which would need a specialist. Please don\u2019t force the foreskin back. We\u2019ll treat the cause and review.', b:['Inflammation of the glans explanation','Usually candidal/irritant \u2014 antifungal + hygiene','Check glucose (diabetes link)','Watch for scarring/lichen sclerosus','Don\u2019t force foreskin; review'] },
  { c:'Pilonidal sinus', t:'Kidneys', m:'This painful, leaking swelling at the top of the buttock crease is a pilonidal abscess \u2014 an infection in a small pocket that forms there around trapped hairs, common in younger people who sit a lot. The important thing is that an abscess needs to be drained \u2014 letting the trapped pus out is what relieves it; antibiotics alone won\u2019t fix it, and I\u2019ll only add them if the surrounding skin is spreading-red or you\u2019re feverish. So I\u2019ll arrange that drainage urgently with good pain relief. Once it settles, the underlying pocket often needs the surgeons to deal with it properly, because it tends to recur. To reduce that: keep the area clean and dry, and manage the hair.', b:['Infected pocket around hairs explanation','Abscess needs drainage (not antibiotics alone)','Urgent drainage + analgesia','Surgical referral for the sinus','Prevention (hygiene/hair)'] },

  /* ---------- Blood ---------- */
  { c:'Chronic lymphocytic leukaemia', t:'Blood', m:'I can see how frightening the word \u201cleukaemia\u201d is, so let me explain properly, because the reality is often far more reassuring than it sounds. Your blood shows a raised number of one type of white cell, which looks like CLL \u2014 chronic lymphocytic leukaemia. It is technically a blood cancer, but it\u2019s very often slow-growing, and many people \u2014 especially those diagnosed by chance while feeling well, like you \u2014 never need treatment and live a normal lifespan. For many, the approach is \u201cwatch and wait\u201d: simply monitoring with blood tests, treating only if it ever becomes active. I\u2019ll refer you to the blood specialists. One practical thing: keep your vaccinations up to date and see us promptly with infections.', b:['Acknowledge the fear','Honest: it is a cancer but often indolent','Many never need treatment','Watch-and-wait explanation','Infection/vaccination advice'] },
  { c:'Myeloma', t:'Blood', m:'Your tests point towards a condition called myeloma, which I\u2019ll explain and then get the specialists involved quickly. Myeloma is a cancer of a type of cell in the bone marrow that normally makes antibodies; when these cells grow out of control they crowd the marrow and affect the bones, kidneys and blood \u2014 which is why you\u2019ve had the bone pain, tiredness and these blood changes. I won\u2019t pretend it isn\u2019t serious, but it\u2019s very treatable: modern treatments can control it well, often for years, and there\u2019s a lot of support. I\u2019m referring you urgently to haematology. We\u2019ll go through everything together, and you won\u2019t be facing it alone \u2014 bring someone with you if it helps.', b:['Marrow/antibody-cell cancer explanation','Why bone/kidney/blood affected','Honest but treatable','Urgent haematology referral','Support/non-abandonment'] },

  /* ---------- Men\u2019s health ---------- */
  { c:'Erectile dysfunction', t:'Men\u2019s health', m:'Erectile dysfunction is very common and very treatable, and there\u2019s no need to be embarrassed. An erection needs good blood flow, healthy nerves and the right hormones and mood all working together, so when it\u2019s not working it can be physical, psychological, or both. Importantly, it can be an early warning sign of the same processes that affect the heart\u2019s arteries, so I\u2019ll check things like blood pressure, sugar and cholesterol \u2014 treating those helps you in more ways than one. We\u2019ll review any medicines that contribute, and tackle stress or relationship factors. The tablets like sildenafil work well for most men. So this is fixable, and it\u2019s also a useful prompt to look after your overall health.', b:['Common, treatable, destigmatise','Blood flow/nerves/hormones/mood explanation','Cardiovascular warning sign \u2014 check risk','Review meds + psychological factors','Effective tablets (sildenafil)'] },
  { c:'Premature ejaculation', t:'Men\u2019s health', m:'Thank you for raising this \u2014 it\u2019s common and treatable, and nothing to be embarrassed about. Premature ejaculation simply means finishing sooner than you\u2019d like, with a sense of not having control, and it often gets tangled up with anxiety, which makes it worse. There are several things that genuinely help: simple techniques like the \u201cstop-start\u201d and \u201csqueeze\u201d methods, which you can practise with your partner; numbing creams or sprays that reduce sensitivity; and a tablet \u2014 a type of antidepressant \u2014 that delays things, taken either before sex or daily. I\u2019ll also check that erections themselves are firm, because rushing to avoid losing an erection can drive this. It really does improve.', b:['Common, treatable, destigmatise','Definition + anxiety link','Behavioural techniques + topical','SSRI option','Check for coexisting ED'] },
  { c:'Peyronie\u2019s disease', t:'Men\u2019s health', m:'I\u2019m glad you came \u2014 this is a recognised condition called Peyronie\u2019s disease, and there\u2019s nothing to be embarrassed about. Scar tissue forms in the wall of the penis, which is what causes the bend, the lump you can feel, and the pain. It tends to go through two stages: an early, painful, changing phase, and then a settled phase. The pain usually eases and the curve often stabilises over time \u2014 so we generally don\u2019t rush to fix it surgically; we let it settle, usually about a year, before considering an operation if it\u2019s still causing problems. I\u2019ll refer you to the specialists, and we\u2019ll address how it\u2019s affecting you and your relationship too, which matters just as much.', b:['Scar-tissue/plaque explanation','Two phases (active \u2192 stable)','Let it stabilise before surgery','Specialist referral','Address psychosexual impact'] },

  /* ---------- Women\u2019s health ---------- */
  { c:'Heavy periods', t:'Women\u2019s health', m:'Heavy menstrual bleeding that affects your life is common, and you don\u2019t have to just put up with it. There are many causes \u2014 often no specific abnormality, sometimes fibroids, hormonal or, occasionally, a thickened lining \u2014 so I\u2019ll examine and check your blood count for anaemia, which heavy bleeding can cause. The good news is that effective treatments don\u2019t necessarily mean surgery. We can reduce the bleeding with tablets taken during your period, or \u2014 very effectively \u2014 the hormonal coil, which often dramatically lightens periods and doubles as contraception. If you\u2019d prefer something non-hormonal, there are options too. We\u2019ll find what fits you, and look for any underlying cause that needs treating.', b:['Common; don\u2019t put up with it','Causes + check for anaemia','Treatments aren\u2019t just surgery','Hormonal coil very effective','Tailor to her preferences'] },
  { c:'Fibroids', t:'Women\u2019s health', m:'Fibroids are very common, non-cancerous growths of muscle in the wall of the womb \u2014 think of them like firm lumps in the muscle, ranging from tiny to large. Many cause no problems at all, but depending on their size and position they can cause heavy or prolonged periods, pelvic pressure or discomfort. The reassuring news is they\u2019re benign and we treat based on your symptoms, not just their presence. Options range from medicines to lighten bleeding or shrink them, through to procedures or surgery if they\u2019re troublesome \u2014 and they often shrink after the menopause. I\u2019ll arrange a scan to map them and check your blood count. We\u2019ll choose an approach around your symptoms and your plans, including any wish for fertility.', b:['Benign womb-muscle growths explanation','Symptoms depend on size/position','Treat symptoms, not presence','Range of options; shrink post-menopause','Scan + consider fertility plans'] },
  { c:'Postmenopausal bleeding', t:'Women\u2019s health', m:'Any bleeding after the menopause \u2014 once you\u2019ve had no periods for a year \u2014 always needs checking, even if it\u2019s just a spot. I want to be honest about why: most causes are harmless, like a thin, dry lining, but it can occasionally be the first sign of a cancer of the womb lining, which is very treatable when caught early \u2014 and that\u2019s exactly why we don\u2019t ignore it. So I\u2019m referring you urgently to the gynaecology clinic, where they\u2019ll do a scan of the womb lining and often a quick sample. Please try not to panic \u2014 the great majority turn out to be nothing sinister \u2014 but it\u2019s important we look properly. You did the right thing coming in.', b:['Always investigate PMB','Honest: usually benign, but cancer possible','Early womb cancer is treatable','Urgent gynae referral (scan + biopsy)','Reassure proportionately'] },
  { c:'Hyperemesis gravidarum', t:'Women\u2019s health', m:'You\u2019re right that this isn\u2019t \u201cjust morning sickness.\u201d When you can\u2019t keep down even water, you\u2019re passing little urine and losing weight, that\u2019s a recognised condition called hyperemesis gravidarum, and it needs proper treatment \u2014 it\u2019s common, and it\u2019s not your fault. The pregnancy hormones drive severe nausea and vomiting, and the priority is to stop you getting dehydrated. Because you can\u2019t keep fluids down, the safest thing is fluids into a vein, so I\u2019ll arrange that today. There are anti-sickness medicines that are safe in pregnancy, and we add a vitamin to keep you well. It usually eases as pregnancy goes on. Come back urgently if you still can\u2019t keep fluids down.', b:['Not \u201cjust morning sickness\u201d','Dehydration is the priority','IV fluids when can\u2019t tolerate oral','Safe antiemetics + thiamine','Reassure + safety-net'] },
  { c:'Endometriosis', t:'Women\u2019s health', m:'Endometriosis is a condition where tissue similar to the womb lining grows outside the womb \u2014 on the ovaries, pelvis and elsewhere. Each month that tissue responds to your hormones and bleeds, but it has nowhere to escape, causing inflammation, pain and sometimes scarring \u2014 which is why you get severe period pain, pain with sex, and sometimes difficulty conceiving. I\u2019m sorry if this has been dismissed as \u201cnormal period pain\u201d before, because it often is; it\u2019s real and there\u2019s often a long delay to diagnosis. We can manage pain and the hormonal drive with painkillers and hormonal treatments like the pill or coil, and the gynaecologists can investigate and treat further. We\u2019ll also factor in any plans for fertility.', b:['Tissue outside the womb explanation','Why pain/subfertility','Validate (often dismissed/delayed)','Hormonal + analgesic management','Gynae referral + fertility'] },
  { c:'Mastitis', t:'Women\u2019s health', m:'Mastitis is inflammation of the breast, common in breastfeeding when milk isn\u2019t draining well and backs up, sometimes with infection \u2014 which is why one area is red, hot, painful and you feel fluey. The single most important treatment is to keep the milk moving: keep breastfeeding or expressing from that side, because draining the breast is what clears it \u2014 stopping makes it worse. Warmth before feeds, gentle massage and painkillers help. If it\u2019s not settling within about 24 hours, or you\u2019re getting worse with a fever, you may need antibiotics, which are safe to take while feeding. Come back if a tender lump persists after it settles, or if a painful red area is getting worse despite all this.', b:['Milk stasis \u00b1 infection explanation','Keep the milk moving (keep feeding)','Warmth/massage/analgesia','Antibiotics if not settling/unwell','Safety-net persistent lump'] },

  /* ---------- Eyes ---------- */
  { c:'Age-related macular degeneration', t:'Eyes', m:'This affects the macula, the central part of the retina that gives you sharp, detailed vision \u2014 which is why your central sight is blurred and straight lines look wavy, while your side vision is fine. There are two types, and which one matters a lot. The \u201cdry\u201d type is gradual and we support it with aids and lifestyle; the \u201cwet\u201d type comes on faster and is treatable with injections that can save sight \u2014 but only if we act quickly. Because your distortion is fairly recent, I\u2019m referring you urgently to the eye clinic to check for the treatable type. Stopping smoking is the single biggest thing you can do. I\u2019ll give you a grid to monitor each eye \u2014 sudden change means urgent review.', b:['Central retina explanation','Dry (gradual) vs wet (rapid, treatable)','Urgent referral for recent distortion','Smoking cessation','Amsler-grid safety-net'] },
  { c:'Acute glaucoma', t:'Eyes', m:'This is an eye emergency, so I\u2019m going to act quickly. Acute glaucoma happens when the pressure inside the eye rises suddenly because the fluid can\u2019t drain \u2014 that\u2019s why your eye is red and agonising, your vision\u2019s blurred with haloes round lights, and you feel sick. It\u2019s not a migraine or a bug. If the pressure isn\u2019t brought down promptly it can damage the sight, within hours \u2014 so you need the emergency eye unit right now, not a wait-and-see. I\u2019m arranging that immediately and will call ahead. The good news is that treated quickly, the pressure can be brought down and the sight protected. Don\u2019t drive yourself \u2014 we\u2019ll sort how you get there.', b:['Sudden rise in eye pressure explanation','Red painful eye + haloes + nausea','Sight-threatening within hours','Immediate emergency eye referral','Reassure if treated promptly'] },
  { c:'Anterior uveitis', t:'Eyes', m:'Anterior uveitis is inflammation inside the front of the eye \u2014 the coloured part and the structures around it become inflamed, which is why the eye is red, achy and very sensitive to light, with blurred vision. It\u2019s different from conjunctivitis, which is gritty and not usually painful. It needs prompt treatment by the eye specialists, with steroid drops to settle the inflammation and drops to ease the spasm and pain, so I\u2019m referring you urgently. It often settles well, but it can recur, and it\u2019s sometimes linked to conditions elsewhere in the body, which we\u2019d look into. Don\u2019t ignore a painful red eye with light sensitivity \u2014 that combination always deserves a same-day eye assessment.', b:['Inflammation inside the front of the eye','Red, painful, photophobic (not conjunctivitis)','Urgent ophthalmology + steroid drops','Can recur / systemic associations','Painful red eye = same-day'] },
  { c:'Dry eye syndrome', t:'Eyes', m:'Dry eye is very common and, although it sounds odd, it can make the eyes water \u2014 because poor-quality tears trigger reflex watering. The tear film that keeps the surface smooth and comfortable isn\u2019t working well, so you get grittiness, burning, blurring that clears when you blink, and tired eyes, especially with screens. It\u2019s harmless but irritating, and very manageable. The mainstay is regular lubricating drops \u2014 \u201cartificial tears\u201d \u2014 used often, not just when bad, plus warm compresses and lid hygiene if the eyelid glands are involved. Taking screen breaks and blinking fully helps. It\u2019s usually a long-term thing we keep comfortable rather than cure. See an optician or come back if vision is affected or one eye becomes painful and red.', b:['Poor tear film explanation','Paradoxical watering','Harmless but manageable','Regular lubricating drops + lid care','Screen advice + safety-net'] },
  { c:'Retinal detachment', t:'Eyes', m:'I need to be straight with you: sudden visual changes like this are an eye emergency, and the fact it doesn\u2019t hurt doesn\u2019t make it safe to wait. The flashes and floaters followed by a shadow or curtain coming across your vision suggest the retina \u2014 the light-sensitive layer at the back of the eye \u2014 may be peeling away. This is time-critical, because the sooner it\u2019s repaired, the better the chance of saving the central sight. So I\u2019m arranging for you to be seen by the emergency eye service today \u2014 not the weekend. I can\u2019t examine the back of your eye over the phone, but they can. Please don\u2019t drive yourself there.', b:['Painless \u2260 safe to wait','Flashes/floaters \u2192 curtain = detachment','Time-critical for central vision','Same-day emergency eye service','Don\u2019t self-drive'] },

  /* ---------- ENT ---------- */
  { c:'Benign positional vertigo', t:'ENT', m:'That brief, intense spinning when you turn over in bed or tip your head back is benign positional vertigo \u2014 a real mouthful, but reassuringly harmless. Tiny crystals that normally sit in one part of the balance organ in your inner ear have come loose and drifted into a canal where they don\u2019t belong, so certain head movements send a false \u201cspinning\u201d signal to the brain. It\u2019s not a stroke or anything sinister. The good news is there\u2019s a simple sequence of head movements \u2014 the Epley manoeuvre \u2014 that repositions the crystals and often fixes it quickly; I can show you. It tends to come and go but settles. Come back if you get other symptoms like weakness, slurred speech, deafness or constant rather than positional dizziness.', b:['Loose inner-ear crystals explanation','Brief, position-triggered, harmless','Epley manoeuvre repositions crystals','Tends to settle','Red-flag safety-net'] },
  { c:'Vestibular neuritis', t:'ENT', m:'Vestibular neuritis is inflammation of the balance nerve in the inner ear, usually after a viral infection \u2014 which is why you\u2019ve had this sudden, constant, severe spinning with nausea, often lasting a day or two then gradually improving. Unlike the brief positional type, this is continuous. It\u2019s unpleasant but not dangerous, and the brain gradually recalibrates over days to weeks. Short-term medication can ease the worst of the spinning and sickness, but we don\u2019t use it for long because it slows that recovery \u2014 gentle movement and balance exercises actually speed it up. I\u2019ve checked there are no signs pointing to anything more serious. Come back if you develop hearing loss, weakness, slurred speech or a severe headache.', b:['Inflamed balance nerve, post-viral','Constant (not positional) vertigo','Self-limiting; brain recalibrates','Short-term meds + balance exercises','Central red-flag safety-net'] },
  { c:'Tinnitus', t:'ENT', m:'Tinnitus is the perception of a sound \u2014 ringing, buzzing or hissing \u2014 without an external source. It\u2019s very common and, importantly, usually not a sign of anything dangerous; often it\u2019s linked to some hearing changes, noise exposure or stress, and the brain \u201cturns up\u201d its own background signal. There\u2019s often no instant cure, but a lot helps: treating any hearing loss (hearing aids frequently reduce it), background sound to take the edge off, and techniques to stop it dominating your attention, because the more you focus on it the louder it seems. I\u2019ll check your ears and hearing. One thing I do check for \u2014 tinnitus in just one ear, or with one-sided hearing loss, I\u2019d investigate further.', b:['Internal sound perception explanation','Usually not dangerous','Treat hearing loss; sound enrichment','Attention/CBT-style strategies','Unilateral red flag'] },
  { c:'Otitis externa', t:'ENT', m:'This is otitis externa \u2014 inflammation of the ear canal, basically an infection of the skin lining it, very common with swimming and, honestly, with cotton-bud use, which scratches the canal and pushes debris in. That\u2019s why it\u2019s itchy and painful, especially when you touch the ear, with some discharge. The treatment is ear drops \u2014 an antibiotic with a steroid \u2014 rather than tablets, plus cleaning the ear so the drops get in, and painkillers. Crucially, stop the cotton buds and keep the ear dry while it settles. If you\u2019re a keen swimmer we can talk about keeping water out. Come back if it spreads to the skin around the ear, you get a fever, or \u2014 especially with diabetes \u2014 the pain becomes severe.', b:['Canal skin inflammation explanation','Swimming/cotton-bud cause','Topical drops + aural cleaning (not tablets)','Stop cotton buds; keep dry','Spreading/diabetic red flags'] },
  { c:'Eustachian tube dysfunction', t:'ENT', m:'That blocked, full, muffled feeling in your ear \u2014 and the popping \u2014 is eustachian tube dysfunction. There\u2019s a small tube connecting the middle ear to the back of the nose that normally opens to equalise pressure, like the way your ears pop on a plane; when it\u2019s not opening properly, usually after a cold or with allergies, pressure builds and sound is dampened. It\u2019s harmless and usually settles on its own over a week or two as the lining recovers. Things that help: swallowing, yawning, chewing gum, and the technique of pinching your nose and gently blowing to pop the ears. Treating any cold or allergy underneath helps. Come back if it persists for several weeks, or your hearing doesn\u2019t recover.', b:['Pressure-equalising tube explanation','Post-cold/allergy cause','Harmless, self-limiting','Self-pop techniques + treat cause','Safety-net persistence'] },
  { c:'Nosebleeds', t:'ENT', m:'Most nosebleeds come from a network of fragile little vessels at the front of the nose, which can break with dryness, picking, or just spontaneously \u2014 and they look more dramatic than they are. The most important thing is getting the first aid right, because a lot of people do it wrong: sit up, lean forward (not back), and pinch the soft part of the nose firmly for a full 10 to 15 minutes without letting go to check. Afterwards, avoid picking and blowing, and a little moisturiser inside helps prevent more. If you\u2019re on blood thinners, that makes them last longer, so we\u2019ll review that. Get urgent help if a bleed won\u2019t stop after proper pressure, it\u2019s pouring down your throat, or you feel faint.', b:['Fragile front-of-nose vessels explanation','Correct first aid (lean forward, pinch soft part 10\u201315 min)','Prevent recurrence (no picking, moisturiser)','Review anticoagulants','Uncontrolled-bleed safety-net'] },

  /* ---------- Children ---------- */
  { c:'Kawasaki disease', t:'Children', m:'You were right to keep pushing \u2014 six days of high fever that won\u2019t come down, with red eyes, cracked lips, a rash and swollen hands, is not just a virus, and there\u2019s a condition I\u2019m concerned about called Kawasaki disease. It\u2019s an inflammation of blood vessels, and the reason we act fast is that, untreated, it can affect the blood vessels around the heart \u2014 and treatment within roughly the first ten days greatly reduces that risk. So this is urgent, not wait-and-see. I\u2019m referring your child to the children\u2019s team to be seen today; they\u2019ll confirm it, do a heart scan, and treat with immunoglobulin and aspirin if it\u2019s Kawasaki. You did exactly the right thing trusting your instinct.', b:['Prolonged fever + features ≠ \u201cjust a virus\u201d','Vasculitis affecting coronary vessels','Treat within ~10 days','Urgent same-day paediatrics','Validate the parent'] },
  { c:'Febrile seizure', t:'Children', m:'A febrile seizure is a fit brought on by a fever in a young child, usually with an ordinary infection \u2014 the developing brain is sensitive to a rapid rise in temperature. I know it\u2019s absolutely terrifying to witness, but the reassuring facts are that simple febrile seizures are common, brief, and don\u2019t cause brain damage or mean your child has epilepsy. Most children grow out of them by around five or six. If one happens: keep your child safe on their side, don\u2019t put anything in the mouth, and time it. Call 999 if it lasts more than five minutes, or one follows another. Otherwise, treat fevers for comfort, and seek help if you\u2019re worried about the underlying infection.', b:['Fever-triggered seizure in young child','Frightening but usually benign','Not epilepsy/brain damage; outgrown','First-aid + when to call 999','Manage the underlying illness'] },
  { c:'Picky eating', t:'Children', m:'The most reassuring thing first \u2014 I\u2019ve plotted her growth and she\u2019s thriving, active and developing well, which tells me she IS getting what she needs, even though mealtimes don\u2019t feel like it. Picky eating at this age is incredibly common; toddlers are naturally wary of new foods, and it\u2019s a phase most grow out of \u2014 it\u2019s not a reflection of your cooking or parenting. A few things genuinely help: eat together so she sees you enjoying food; keep offering new foods without pressure, because it can take ten or more tries; and avoid forcing, bribing or battling, which backfire. Limit snacks, milk and juice between meals so she\u2019s hungry, and keep mealtimes short and relaxed. She doesn\u2019t need tests or supplements while she\u2019s thriving.', b:['Growth is the key reassurance','Common, normal phase','Repeated low-pressure exposure','No force/bribery/battles','No tests/supplements if thriving'] },
  { c:'Cow\u2019s milk protein allergy', t:'Children', m:'It sounds like your baby may be reacting to the protein in cow\u2019s milk \u2014 the immune system treating it as a threat, which can cause the tummy upset, reflux-like symptoms, skin rashes or unsettledness. It\u2019s common and very manageable, and importantly it\u2019s usually outgrown by toddler age. The mainstay is removing cow\u2019s milk protein: if you\u2019re breastfeeding, that means cow\u2019s milk out of your diet; if formula-fed, we switch to a special hydrolysed formula where the protein is broken down. We\u2019ll see a clear improvement if that\u2019s the cause, and later carefully reintroduce to confirm and to track when it\u2019s outgrown. I\u2019ll involve a dietitian to keep nutrition on track. Seek urgent help for any sudden swelling, breathing difficulty or severe reaction.', b:['Immune reaction to milk protein','Common, usually outgrown','Remove cow\u2019s milk protein (diet/formula)','Reintroduce to confirm; dietitian','Anaphylaxis safety-net'] }

]);
